.TH KEYSTASH 1 "July 2026" "keystash 0.3.9" "keystash User Manual"
.SH NAME
keystash \- Secure offline TUI and CLI password manager written in Rust
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B keystash
[\-\-no\-sync] [tui|init|add|list|search|show|copy|generate|import|export|delete|reset|sync|help]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B keystash
is a lightweight, secure, and completely offline password manager. It features an interactive Terminal User Interface (TUI) built on Ratatui, secure Argon2id key derivation, column-level XChaCha20-Poly1305 AEAD encryption, unencrypted Bitwarden JSON importing, and two-way logical git database synchronization.
.PP
Running
.B keystash
without any commands launches the interactive TUI.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-\-no\-sync
Bypass all Git synchronization processes (startup pull, database updates thread, and exit push). Useful for offline access or slow connections.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B init
Initialize a new local password vault database and configure your Master Password.
.TP
.B add \fItitle\fR \fIcategory\fR \fIusername\fR [\fIurl\fR]
Insert a new credential. The CLI will securely prompt you for your password. Double quotes are required for arguments containing spaces (e.g. keystash add "My Google Account" "Email" "user@gmail.com").
.TP
.B list [\-r|\-\-reveal]
List all stored credentials in the vault. Passwords are masked by default unless \-r or \-\-reveal is supplied. WARNING: Revealing all passwords dumps them in plaintext into the terminal scrollback buffer. Use with caution.
.TP
.B search \fIquery\fR [\-r|\-\-reveal]
Search for matching credentials across titles, categories, usernames, or URLs. Passwords are masked by default unless \-r or \-\-reveal is supplied. A query starting with a dash is matched literally as long as it isn't \-r/\-\-reveal itself; use "keystash search \-\- \-yourquery" if it collides with a flag name.
.TP
.B show \fIid\fR [\-r|\-\-reveal]
Show a detailed view of a secret (including notes). Passwords and notes are masked by default unless \-r or \-\-reveal is supplied.
.TP
.B copy \fIid\fR [\fIusername\fR|\fIpassword\fR|\fIurl\fR]
Copy the target secret field to the system clipboard (automatically clearing it after the configured delay, default 5 seconds). Defaults to copying the password.
.TP
.B generate [\-l \fIlength\fR] [\-\-no\-uppercase] [\-\-no\-numbers] [\-\-no\-symbols] [\-\-uppercase] [\-\-numbers] [\-\-symbols]
Generate a random secure password, print it (excluding ambiguous characters), and copy it to the clipboard for the configured delay. Your options are saved as your new defaults.
.TP
.B import \fIpath/to/backup_file\fR
Import login credentials from unencrypted files (supports Bitwarden JSON, KeyStash CSV, Brave/Chrome CSV, Firefox CSV, LastPass CSV, KeePassXC CSV, and 1Password CSV).
.TP
.B export \fIpath/to/output_file.csv\fR
Export all vault credentials to an unencrypted CSV file (with permissions restricted to 0600 on Unix).
.TP
.B delete \fIid\fR
Delete a credential record by its database ID.
.TP
.B reset
Nuke the local database file after confirming via a verification prompt.
.TP
.B sync
Force a manual logical merge and synchronization with your configured Git remote.
.TP
.B change-password
Change Master Password and re-encrypt all stored vault secrets using a newly derived key.
.TP
.B help, -h, --help
Show the standard command-line help block.
.SH TUI KEYBINDINGS
Within the interactive dashboard, use the following keys:
.TP
.B Tab / Shift+Tab
Cycle focus forward/backward between the Categories list, Credentials list, and Details pane.
.TP
.B Arrow Up / Down
Scroll through lists item-by-item.
.TP
.B PageUp / PageDown
Scroll lists page-by-page.
.TP
.B Space
Mark or unmark a credential for mass actions.
.TP
.B / (Slash)
Focus the search bar to filter credentials by query text. Press Enter or Esc to exit search entry.
.TP
.B a
Add a new credential.
.TP
.B e
Edit the selected credential.
.TP
.B d
Delete the selected credential (or all marked credentials if any exist).
.TP
.B v
Toggle password plaintext visibility in the Details pane.
.TP
.B c
Copy username to clipboard (clears automatically in configured delay, default 5s).
.TP
.B p
Copy decrypted password to clipboard (clears automatically in configured delay, default 5s).
.TP
.B u
Copy website URL to clipboard (clears automatically in configured delay, default 5s).
.TP
.B m
Open the Change Master Password form overlay.
.TP
.B s
Force a manual sync with the configured Git remote.
.TP
.B i
Open the Import modal popup to import credentials from unencrypted backups.
.TP
.B x
Open the Export modal popup to export credentials (all or selected) to an unencrypted CSV.
.TP
.B h
Check the selected password (or marked passwords if any exist) on HaveIBeenPwned.
.TP
.B H
Check all passwords in the vault on HaveIBeenPwned asynchronously in a background thread.
.TP
.B D
Open the duplicate credential detector and interactive resolver.
.TP
.B ,
Open the KeyStash settings screen modal.
.TP
.B ?
Toggle the Help & Keybindings modal popup.
.TP
.B Esc
Cancel dialogs, close forms, or exit the application.
.TP
.B q
Same as Esc, except in text-entry fields (Add/Edit form, Change Password, Settings), where it types the letter instead.
.SH SYNCHRONIZATION & MULTI-MACHINE SETUP
If the config folder (~/.config/keystash) is initialized as a Git repository, keystash will automatically synchronize and merge database updates across your machines.
.PP
.B First-time Setup (Device A):
.nf
  cd ~/.config/keystash
  git init
  echo "*" > .gitignore
  echo "!vault.db" >> .gitignore
  git remote add origin <private-git-repo-url>
  git branch -M main
  git add .
  git commit -m "Initial vault backup"
  git push -u origin main
.fi
.PP
.B Adding a New Device (Device B):
.IP
.B WARNING:
DO NOT run "keystash init" on a secondary device. This will generate a different database salt and result in decryption errors. Instead, pull the existing database directly from origin:
.nf
  mkdir -p ~/.config/keystash
  cd ~/.config/keystash
  git init
  echo "*" > .gitignore
  echo "!vault.db" >> .gitignore
  git remote add origin <private-git-repo-url>
  git branch -M main
  git pull origin main
.fi
.SH SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS
.B Layered Encryption (Full Database + Sensitive Fields)
.IP
The entire vault.db file is encrypted with SQLCipher: schema, indexes, and every column, including title, category, username, url, and timestamps. Nothing in the file is readable without the master password—including by anyone with read access to your private Git backup repository. As defense in depth, the password and notes fields are additionally encrypted with XChaCha20-Poly1305 under an independently derived key, so a compromise of the SQLCipher layer alone does not expose them. The Argon2id salt is embedded in the first 16 bytes of vault.db (it is not secret on its own); vaults created before v0.3.6 kept it in a vault.salt sidecar file and are converted automatically on first unlock.
.PP
.B Clipboard Security
.IP
KeyStash automatically clears copied credentials from the system clipboard after the configured delay (default 5 seconds). However, third-party clipboard history managers (like CopyQ or Klipper) can intercept and save copied text. You should configure these managers to ignore copy actions from the "keystash" binary.
.PP
.B Memory Cleansing
.IP
Master passwords and decryption keys are securely zeroized from RAM after use. TUI buffers are pre-allocated and cleared/zeroized in-place to prevent heap reallocation remnants. Locking the vault also drops the open, keyed SQLCipher connection itself, not just the in-memory key, so the vault's encrypted contents aren't left readable through a lingering connection while on the Lock screen.
.PP
.B Schema Migrations
.IP
Database schema integrity checks and upgrades are performed automatically on startup using a custom embedded migrations mechanism.
.PP
.B Deletion Tombstone Pruning
.IP
Deleting a credential leaves a tombstone record behind so the deletion propagates correctly to other devices on their next sync. Tombstones older than 90 days are pruned automatically during sync, so a deleted credential's title and username don't live on in the vault forever; the 90-day window is intentionally generous, giving an infrequently-synced device time to see the deletion before its tombstone disappears.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.config/keystash/vault.db
The local SQLite database storing metadata, validation tokens, and your encrypted secrets.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B XDG_CONFIG_HOME
If set, used to locate the config directory as $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/keystash/ instead of the default. Checked before HOME.
.TP
.B HOME
Used to locate the user's config directory (~/.config/keystash/) when XDG_CONFIG_HOME is not set. If neither is set, KeyStash falls back to ./.config/keystash/ relative to the current directory and prints a warning.
